  "prompt": "What is the proper way to use RSVP out of the following?",
  "response": "RSVP is an acronym for the French phrase \"R\u00e9pondez s'il vous pla\u00eet,\" which translates to \"Please respond\" in English. It is used to request a response from the recipient regarding their attendance to an event. Here\u2019s the proper way to use RSVP in different contexts:\n\n1. **Invitations (Written or Digital):**\n   - **Example:** \"Kindly RSVP by [date] to let us know if you can attend.\"\n   - Include clear instructions on how to respond (e.g., phone number, email address, or online form).\n   - Specify a deadline for the response to help with planning.\n\n2. **Verb Usage:**\n   - **Example:** \"Please RSVP to the event by [date].\"\n   - You can say, \u201cHave you RSVPed yet?\u201d or \u201cDon\u2019t forget to RSVP.\u201d\n\n3. **Formal vs. Informal:**\n   - For formal events, use \"RSVP\" as is: \"We kindly request your RSVP by [date].\"\n   - For casual events, you can simplify it: \"Let us know if you\u2019re coming!\"\n\n4. **Online Invitations:**\n   - Many digital platforms (e.g., Evite, Facebook Events) have built-in RSVP options. Use these to streamline responses.\n\n5. **Responding to an RSVP:**\n   - If you receive an RSVP request, reply by the specified deadline, even if you cannot attend.\n   - Be clear and polite: \u201cThank you for the invitation! I will be attending.\u201d or \u201cUnfortunately, I cannot attend, but I appreciate the invitation.\u201d\n\n### Common Mistakes to Avoid:\n- Don\u2019t assume no response means you\u2019re attending or not attending\u2014always reply explicitly.\n- Avoid using \"RSVP\" as a noun in formal writing (e.g., don\u2019t say, \u201cSend me your RSVP\u201d).\n- Don\u2019t use RSVP redundantly (e.g., \u201cPlease RSVP back\u201d is incorrect because RSVP already implies a response).\n\nBy using RSVP correctly, you ensure clear communication and proper event planning.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
